Here’s a minimal Node.js snippet using the `fetch` API to call an LLM. Replace `YOUR_API_KEY` and `YOUR_MODEL` with your actual values:

javascript
const apiKey = 'YOUR_API_KEY';
const model = 'YOUR_MODEL';

const response = await fetch('https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json',
    'Authorization': `Bearer ${apiKey}`
  },
  body: JSON.stringify({
    model,
    messages: [{ role: 'user', content: 'Hello, how are you?' }],
    max_tokens: 100,
    temperature: 0.7
  })
});

const data = await response.json();
console.log('Response:', data.choices[0].message.content);
console.log('Stop reason:', data.choices[0].finish_reason);
console.log('Usage:', data.usage);

Note: This assumes Node.js 18+ with native `fetch` support. For older versions, use a library like `node-fetch`.

To implement a multi-turn chat manually, maintain a `messages` array that accumulates all user inputs and model responses. On each turn, append the new user message and the previous model response to the array, then send the entire array in the API request. Here’s an example in Node.js:

javascript
const messages = [];

async function chat(prompt) {
  messages.push({ role: 'user', content: prompt });

  const response = await fetch('https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Authorization': `Bearer YOUR_API_KEY`, 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify({ model: 'gpt-3.5-turbo', messages, max_tokens: 100 })
  });

  const data = await response.json();
  const reply = data.choices[0].message.content;
  messages.push({ role: 'assistant', content: reply });
  return reply;
}

// Example usage:
chat('Hello!').then(console.log);
chat('What did I just ask you?').then(console.log);

This approach ensures the model has full context of the conversation but increases token usage and costs linearly with each turn.
